results.body:
The Greenwich lass will strut her stuff on stage in her finest vintage glamour gear as she competes to be the 2014 Miss Perfect Pinup.

The 28-year-old will model daywear, nightwear, lingerie and perform a talent in the NSW finals.

The competition aims to portray women at their finest with magnificent hairstyles, flawless makeup, clothing that is flattering to any body shape and age with good old-fashioned values.

“I have met many beautiful women who not only share a love of vintage clothes, hair and make-up but also a positive, caring and respectful attitude towards each other ,” she said.

More than 20 entries will be competing in a variety of categories including Miss Perfect, Miss Classic, Miss VaVa Voom, Miss Neo and Mr Pinup.

The finals are on at the Blacktown Workers Club on June 29 and tickets are $35 from misspinupaustralian.com.au

results.body:
Emily Patterson has faced a real-life troll along with an outpouring of public support and generosity from those on social media.

Ms Patterson was at Aristocrat Cafe in the Lane Cove Plaza last Monday with her eight-month-old baby James, who was unsettled and crying ahead of his usual sleep time.

After being tutted at by a woman sitting nearby, Ms Patterson said she felt obliged to apologise and take her baby outside cafe.

It was then she overheard the ladies saying she was neglectful.

Another mother present in the cafe and cafe owner Nick Drinias both went to offer Ms Patterson their support, saying she shouldn’t leave the cafe.

Ms Patterson then approached the woman as she left.

“I told her I’m sorry they feel my baby’s disturbed them and she went to town, saying I shouldn’t have let him cry in the pram and was concerned about the patrons being turned away from the noise,” she said. 

Upset, she wrote about the incident on the North Shore Mums Facebook page while the other mother present posted to In The Cove Facebook page.

It attracted about 400 comments on the In the Cove page, plus offers of a complimentary beauty treatment.

Mr Drinias offered free babyccinos for the rest of the week and was offered rugby tickets for supporting Ms Patterson.

“If I wasn’t perhaps as resilient, it could have gone so much worse for me such as if I was a first-time mum and there were a whole lot of other issues, ” she said.

“My main issue is that the poor old sisterhood had taken a beating that day but after receiving so much support online, I felt the sisterhood made a comeback.

“I know there’s a lot in the media about getting breastfeeding to be acceptable in society, but I think the issue is about people judging mothers.

“It’s so tragic that people could be so harsh about others.”

Parent and child stress management specialist Patrice Thomas said mindful meditation can help other parents who find themselves in the same situation.

“Learning how to do that gives you more equanimity in life and a bit more confidence not to take it so personally and put it in the perspective that it warrants,” she said.

“It’s about being mindful of yourself and others.”

She praised the actions of the other woman present and cafe owner.

“I think it shows more about the person making the comments to other people,” she said.

“Good on them for going into bat for her.”

STRESS LESS

Stress management consultant Patrice Thomas will present a workshop for parents.

WHEN July 23

TIME: 7.15pm arrival for 7.30-9.30pm session

WHERE: Pymble Turramurra Kindergarten

ADDRESS: 21 Handley Ave, Turramurra

COST: $25

BOOKINGS: 9449 1445 or director@pymbleturrakindy.org.au

One of the top performers was a five-bedroom house at 90 Collins Rd, which was snapped up prior to auction for $2.88 million.

Selling agent Paul Diks, from Chadwick Real Estate- St Ives, said the 1353 sq m property was bought by a family from Eastgardens who were drawn to its size and presentation.

``It was real colossal property,’’ Mr Diks said.

``We had over 100 groups through and three main parties interested,’’

It sold five days before it was due to be auctioned.

The agent sold another five-bedroom house at 7 Torokina Ave for $1.7 million at auction.

A buyer from Ashfield bought it after an opening bid of $1.7 million, matching the reserve price.

It attracted more than 100 groups through inspections.

Mr Diks said top rated schools in St Ives, including Sydney Grammar Preparatory School and St Ives North Primary School, were responsible for driving up property prices in the area.

``St Ives has been undervalued for many years and now its properly on the map,’’ he said.

``Buyers who are being pushed out of the Killara and Wahroonga markets are also looking to St Ives.

``It also has the convenience of good shopping centres.’’

A buyer has bought a St Ives house after only seeing the property for the first time that day.

The five-bedroom house at 6 Derby St sold for $1.83 million after spirited bidding from five out of nine registered bidders.

An opening bid of $1.6 million increased in increments of $10,000 up until $1.75 million and then continued in increments of $5000.

A late bidder came in at $1.82 million and secure the property at the fall of the hammer.

Selling agents Michael Doran and Giuseppe Princi, of McGrath Pymble, said the high level of interest for a property in the mid to upper price range in St Ives was ”extremely rare’’.

A garden apartment at 5/5 Gillott Way, St Ives, has sold for $980,000 after only two weeks on the market.

LJ Hooker- St Ives agent Peter Ramsay sold it to a St Ives couple were who downsizing two storey house with swimming pool.

The agent fielded a high number inquiries from local buyers looking to downsize, with around 50 groups during the campaign.

It featured three bedrooms, two bathrooms and a courtyard.

It was the top price paid for an apartment in that complex, the agent said.

The school’s agricultural plot has seen two Corriedale lambs born in the past two weeks with three more on the way.

The lambs have provided hands-on lessons for the school’s agricultural classes over the past five years, with the current lambs under the protective watch of the school’s Year 9 agriculture class. 

Head of agriculture Ian Bryson said their two most recent additions were showing an independent streak.

One is very independent, which is good being the first on the park, he said.

“Its mother is protective as well; you get some that don’t seem to worry too much if their lambs wander far off.”

results.body:
The petition for a new skate park at Bob Campbell oval was able to flip the support of Lane Cove Council towards investigating a new skate park at a meeting on Monday night.

The council’s support along with signatures from a surprising number of older residents, has given the campaign an air of hope.

Gathering the signatures were keen skaters 11-year-old Charlie Nicholas, his younger brothers Oliver, 10 and Will, 8 and their friends.

Charlie spoke at the council meeting on Monday night.

“We’ve had a positive response from people of all ages,” he told the meeting

“Some of the older residents have been talking to us, saying how it will be good and it will give us a chance to stop riding on the streets,” he said.

Charlie also said it provided an opportunity for young people to socialise. 

“A skate park is where people can be sociable, spend the whole day and enjoy themselves and get fit instead of playing on the iPad and watching TV,” he told the meeting.

All councillors got on board, voting unanimously to create a working party on the issue, which will now investigate types of skate parks, possible locations and potential funding.

Lane Cove currently has one skate park within the grounds of Blackman Park in Lane Cove West, more specifically known as a flow park.

However, Nicky Nicholas, whose sons started the petition said it was too small. 

“It’s one of those very small parks where you get half a dozen people skating and it’s already full,” she said.

Mrs Nicholas said she often had to drive her sons to the nearest skate parks in Five Dock or Cammeray.

“For the 10 to 15 age group, the services seem to be lacking in the Greenwich area,” she said. 

A Lane Cove Council plan to redevelop Lane Cove Country Club’s clubhouse site including several tennis courts, was revealed in January last year.

In its place a new multipurpose centre was planned to be built, including an indoor skate park among other facilities.

results.body:
Upgrades to the intersection of Pennant Hills Rd and the Pacific Highway in Wahroonga will see $120,000 injected into the area, which has been identified as a major black spot.

Bradfield federal Liberal MP Paul Fletcher welcomed the news and said the government was serious about improving road safety.

“For the people of Bradfield who regularly travel along Pennant Hills Rd and the Pacific Highway, the installation of 100m of raised, deflective kerb will make the intersection safer,” he said.

NRMA director Tim Trumper welcomed the funding commitments, but said there’s still more to be done.

“Although we’re a long way from seeing the quality road and transport network our community deserves, the funding we’ve received today is an important first step,” he said.

The collision occurred around 11.35am today near the Gordon Shopping Centre.

The accident happened at the intersection of Park Ave where emergency services were called to the scene.

The male rider was treated at the scene but died a short time after the incident.

The male driver of the car has not been injured.

Police are investigating the cause of the crash.

GORDON: all n/b lanes on #PacificHwy remain closed at #DumaresqSt after fatal car & motorcycle accident. N/b traffic passing via a s/b lane.

— Live Traffic Sydney (@LiveTrafficSyd) June 20, 2014 

All northbound lanes of the Pacific Highway have been closed to traffic, with cars passing the accident using one southboud lane.

One southbound lane is closed, and the third lane is being used by cars heading south.

Major delays are expected and motorists are being to told to avoid the area by using alternative routes.

More details to come.

Last weekend achieved a solid auction clearance rate of 70 per cent with many houses selling above reserve.

One of the first homes to hit the auction block this Saturday morning is a four-bedroom property at 66 Carranya Rd, Riverview.

66 Carranya Rd, Riverview will be auctioned on Saturday.

It is selling through McGrath Lane Cove agents Beth Ferguson and Michael Ferguson.

The two storey, double brick house is set on a 563sq m block and is situated in a sought-after street close to Riverview College.

It has a price guide of $1.55 million.

In St Ives, a 6000sq m property at 42A Pentecost Ave (East Side), St Ives, will be auctioned at noon through Richardson & Wrench St Ives agent Daniel Cook.

42A Pentecost Ave St Ives, was designed by local architect John Brogan.

The four-bedroom home, aptly named The Forest, was designed by local architect John Brogan and features gardens landscaped by designer Gordon Sykes.

The property overlooks Dalrymple-Hay Nature Reserve and is within easy walking distance of the St Ives Centre.

Another St Ives property going to auction is a five-bedroom house at 6 Derby St.

It is expected to fetch over $1.6 million.

The selling agents are Michael Doran and Giuseppe Princi of McGrath Pymble.

The house is situated in a cul-de-sac and features versatile formal and informal living areas and a level garden with entertainment terrace and swimming pool.

A five-bedroom Killara house at 28 Arnold St will be auctioned at 3pm.

28 Arnold Street Killara 

The property was designed to replicate the feel of a Mediterranean sanctuary.

It has a poolside terrace surrounded and a full sized tennis court surrounded by tropical gardens.

The selling agents are Philip Waller and Samuel Lynch from McGrath — Lindfield.

Amber and her mother Zoe would often walk past and donate to a homeless man in the city named John with had a fox terrier called Carrie.

After a few too many times walking past the forlorn pair, an uneasy feeling about their welfare got the better of Amber.

She did some research and came across Pets in the Park, a charity looking after the welfare of the pets of homeless people.

The group provides assistance for the homeless in managing the financial costs of caring for an animal, such as vaccinations, flea treatment, worming, de-sexing and microchipping.

It was then Amber decided to begin a charity drive called The Carrie Project, after the name of the homeless man’s dog.

“When I saw he had a dog, it sparked something in me and it seemed really unjust knowing how much I love and care for my own dogs,” Amber said.

Dedicating a few hours each week to contacting various companies, big and small, she managed to dig up a large pile of pet care and food supplies.

The supplies have been divided into 50 hampers, to be distributed at next month’s Pets in the Park charity veterinary service for homeless people’s pets in Darlinghurst.

“The response has been amazing. I’ve received donations from lots of big and small companies,” Amber said.

“I’ve been told sometimes (homeless people) will go hungry to feed their dogs, so if they have that covered, they can spend their money on whatever else they need.”

To donate, or for details, go to petsinthepark.org.au.

Artarmon Progress Association member Barry Thompson said the event would be held on a Sunday in early October on the Artarmon Village Green

“It will be a food market on the green with tables and a stage for young musicians to play on,” he said.

“We would like to have something on Wilkes Ave as well and get the businesses to come in with us.”

Mr Thompson founded the Artarmon Village Group with pharmacist Nick Logan and Councillor Michelle Sloane in attempts to revitalise the Hampden Rd shopping strip. “We want to improve the streetscape and the thing that I have been dreaming about is a unifying theme so we all have the same colour across the shops,” Mr Logan said.

Councillor Michelle Sloane said small businesses in the area were struggling and she hoped the markets would give them something to rally around.

“The idea is to get the mix right so people aren’t just quickly parking their car, get subway and leave, we want people to stop and shop, meet up with friends and have a coffee,” she said.

“It’s challenging but it gives us an opportunity to revitalise.”

Willoughby Council has given the Artarmon Village Group a $3000 grant to get the night markets up and running.

The group is planning to run the markets will run quarterly if successful.

“I’ve always been into them since I was five and still love it because it’s a poor man’s version of owning all the cars you’ve ever ­wanted,” he said.

The Artarmon Armchair Racer Slot Car Centre owner said nothing beats the high- pitched sound of the cars at constant speed.

“It’s competitive and ­involves both mechanical and model ­aspects which ­appeal to hobbyists,” he said.

His point was echoed by enthusiast Jeremy Wynne who spends his lunchtime at the track tinkering with the motors and adjusting the gears to beat his colleagues.

“I am a weekend warrior dad who tried to find something to get my 12-year-old son interested in.

“I went to buy a slot car for my boy and a few guys from work joined and it’s become a weekly race meet since,” he said.

Throttle in hand, Mr Wynne said he enjoyed watching the tiny cars cruise around the track.

“The weekly meets have done a lot for staff morale and I love taking out the modified Jaguar as it just rips down the straights.”

results.body:
Born in Estonia on Boxing Day in 1904, she arrived in Australia with her uncle and his family at the age of 22.

The family was looking to relocate as far away from the country as possible under the oppression from German and Russian occupying forces.

After having lived in Paddington, she moved to Lane Cove then Longueville in 1941.

Her daughter Asta said she put her longevity down to having a country diet and fresh air while she was growing up as well as hard work.

“She was a very strong and independent woman and lived by herself after my father died after the age of 70,” she said.

“She was very diligent, always trying to do the right thing.”

She said one of her proud memories was securing work at Mr Jagos tailoring on George St near King St, Sydney only after two days of arriving in Sydney, helped by a recommendation from another Estonian worker.

She continued to produce piece work from her home after getting married in 1934.

At the age of 98 in 2003, she went back to her birth country for the first time since leaving as a young woman to meet her surviving relatives.

Mrs Kallas was survived by her children Asta Kallas, two grandchildren and two great grandchildren. Her son Harold died nine years ago.

results.body:
Lane Cove Council recognised a total of 25 outstanding citizens at its annual citizenship awards on June 4.

Winner of the sports award was Jarryd Hughes, 19, who in December 2013 secured his maiden victory and world number 1 ranking at the Snowboard Cross World Cup held in Lake Louise, Canada. He then went on to represent Australia at Sochi Winter Olympics in January.

The young achiever award went to Gabriel Gregory, who not only achieved the highest ATAR score in his HSC last year was also dux of Sydney Grammar School and participating in a number of extra-curricular activities.

Saint Ignatius College student James Ephraums, who won the arts, music and culture award was the first student at the Riverview school to be named music captain for more than one year.

He is already a prolific professional performer, having been a member of the Sydney Youth Orchestra since 2012 and performed as a soloist with the internationally-acclaimed opera singer Amelia Farrugia

The evening culminated in the announcement of Lyndall McNally as the recipient of the Citizen of the Year Award after more than 15 years as president of the Lane Cove Youth Orchestra and an active member on a number of local committees including for the annual Cameraygal Festival. 

An estimated 100 people attended the award presentation evening held in the Lane Cove Council chambers.

Leadership and community service awards went to taekwondo leader Fabian Peters who created an anti-bullying app and helped students raise funds for one of their peers who was diagnosed with leukaemia; Linley Point Neighbourhood Watch Coordinator Greg Griffiths who has actively helped to reduce crime; 89-year-old Peter Bright who has tended to the gardens at Lane Cove Bowling Club for some 30 years; and Frances de Jong who helps to run the St Michael’s church garage sale, which last celebrated its 10th year and highest fundraising result to date.

results.body:
Now it’s available in Chatswood.

Hurricane’s Express has opened at the Anderson St Dining Precinct in Westfield Chatswood, offering their famous ribs and burgers to the people of the north shore.

Owner Craig Goldberg was a co-founder of the original Hurricane’s on Bondi Beach, which has built up a reputation for their secret sauce.

“It has that flavour that you can’t find anywhere,” he said.

“It was my father’s recipe and it was the perfect compliment to ribs and burgers. He still makes it for us. It’s the original recipe that we have been using for 20 years in Australia and many years in South Africa before that.”

The Hurricane’s philosophy is to source the best local ingredients, prepare them with care and keep combinations simple. Their signature dishes include pork, beef and lamb ribs, but if you feel like both red and white meat, you can get a chicken breast and rib duo.

Other favourites for meat eaters include jumbo chicken wings, pulled pork, rump steak and a double decker burger.

“We have char grillers which are specially made for us,” he said.

Their extensive menu has something for everyone with a veggie stack for vegetarians, and salads for a light meal. Goldberg described the restaurant as a casual dining experience, where customers can eat in or take away.

“They have the cinema upstairs, I’m sure they wouldn’t mind you taking it up there,” he said.

DETAILS:

WHERE: Anderson Dining Precinct, Westfield Chatswood

OPEN: Monday to Sunday, 11am to late

The day started with a Walkathon, with the children walking to fundraise for the school.

P & C vice president Diana Bogeff said they raised about $7000 by the end of the day.

“We’re still expecting to collect more money from the walkathon. We’re expecting roughly $15,000,” she said.

GALLERY: Gordon East Public School’s sports carnival

“Adam Kwasnik, formerly of the Central Coast Mariners, he warmed up the kids and had them do a small football workout session.

“This is the first time we held this type of event. The kids love playing soccer, so we thought we’d incorporate it with the World Cup.”

The day was full of activities, with the drizzling rain not stopping the students from having a good time.

Ms Bogeff said Western Sydney Wanderers player Daniel Alessi even played on the muddy oval.

“He said he would play some games with them, even though he wasn’t arranged for that,” she said.

“I was worried about him that he would slip over.”

Ms Bogeff said the school tried to run a different event each year.

She said this was a popular event, but they always arranged days that would appeal to everyone.

“We’re a really small school, but we’re very united. Everybody knows everybody,” she said.

results.body:
“Over a period of time I lost my job, I lost my marriage and then really began a five-year episode of depression which my psychiatrist described as the worst he’d ever treated,” he said.

The Gordon resident, who was joint managing director of a technology company during the dotcom crash in 2000, said he almost gave in before realising he still had a lot to live for.

His words came during Men’s Health Week which ended on Sunday.

“I had a suicidal attempt and gradually came out of it through a combination of exercise, seeing family and friends and working again by volunteering,” he said.

While depression is an illness that can affect anyone at any time, statistics show Australian men account for 78 per cent of suicides, 84 per cent of preventable cancers and 61 per cent of deaths due to heart disease.

In the past year, 25 per cent of men haven’t seen a doctor compared with 10 per cent of women, which is why Mr Cowan hopes his confessions may help to break the conspiracy of silence that has long surrounded depression in Aussie men.

“To a large extent men are socialised to be problem solvers and sort things out but when we can’t we struggle a bit,” he said.

“I didn’t feel comfortable sharing what I thought was a weakness.

Around 1 in 3 workers in the financial & insurance sectors experience a mental heath condition. PwC report @beyondblue #WorkplaceMH

— PwC Australia (@PwC_AU) June 16, 2014 

But what Mr Cowan said he learnt from interviewing 4000 people for his book Back from the Brink  is that you shouldn’t ignore the signs.

“I kept pushing myself when the market collapsed and the drive which helped my success also contributed to my demise,” he said.

“The stress relationship is a bell curve and the big insight for me is learning where the top of the bell curve is and then when I reach it, knowing how to pull back from some of my commitments,” he said.

Diagnosis of depression in men isn’t easy and Mr Cowan said you can often feel like you’re a burden.

“When you have a cast on your foot people will go out of their way to open doors, do your shopping but people as a whole tend to stay away when you’ve got a mental issue,” he said.

While it’s common for women to acknowledge their sadness and sagging self esteem, Mr Cowan who is also an ambassador for RU OK Day, said men shouldn’t be afraid to share theirs.

“Reach out to people you trust, tell them what’s happening and that you’re not coping and ask for their support,” he said.

Beyond Blue is a counselling service that can assist you if you’re feeling down 1300 224 636.

results.body:
The pair will represent Australia at the Oceania Area Athletics Championships at Rarotonga.

Bartholomew, 19, of Pymble, is competing in the 200m and 400m.

“I think it’s a good competition to start on, with Oceania being a smaller amount of countries,” she said.

“It’s not quite on the entire world scale, so it’s a good one to start on and get accustomed to it.

“It’s hard to say how I’ll go because I don’t really know the competition that’s there, but a medal finish would be fantastic.”

Fitzsimmons, 19, of Turramurra, said he was competing in the same events.

He said he was “pretty stoked” to be selected.

“I applied because I didn’t make it for the world juniors due to illness,” he said.

“I’m hoping for a personal best time and hopefully just to do well for Australia.”

Bartholomew said she had been taking her training session by session, working on her endurance and speed.

“I’ve always found it difficult in the 400 to get the balance between endurance and speed,” she said.

“It’s tough, but I think this season I did a little better to get that.”

The championships are on from June 24-26.

results.body:
This year the owner of Divine Creatures in Willoughby is on the prowl for a win, after being named an award finalist for a second time. “I’m feeling optimistic this time, so fingers crossed,” she said.

CLICK HERE to read last year’s story

Ms Dos Santos pounced upon the opportunity to grow the business after last year’s award.

Plans are under way to expand the current hotel, undertake renovations and open up a new site in sometime over the next two years.

A former vet, Ms Dos Santos was appointed to the Pet Industry Association as an adviser update the codes of practice for pet boarding.

She is also in discussions with the Cat Protection Society over a link to cat adoption services.

“The award gave me the confidence to grow my business; I feel like I’ve been unleashed,” she said.

“When big names in Australian business tell me we I have an amazing business it gives you that confidence and has empowered me to do anything I wanted with it.”

Divine Creatures was one of seven businesses in the state nominated in the micro business category. 

She said the key to her success was thinking like a customer.

“Walk through your business as if you’re a client and that should flow through to your staff,” she said.

Award winners for NSW will be announced on July 1.

Other north shore businesses were nominated as two of six finalists in the medium business category for NSW in the Telstra Business Awards. They were:

 Software and IT support service business Distribution Central created 10 years ago by Scott Frew and Nick Verykios and based in St Leonards

 Direct debit system business Ezypay Pty Ltd was started by George Holman in 1998 and is based in West Chatswood

results.body:
The 11-year-old St Pius X College student was recently selected to represent NSW in the School Sport Australia Basketball Championships in the under-12 team.

Michael was selected for the Combined Independent Schools team that dominated the Primary School Sports Association tournament, going through undefeated in Pool A before winning the semi-final against Sydney North 42-25.

Michael said he was selected for the NSW team after the state coaches recognised his skill in the grand final against North West, where his team won 38-36.

“I played good defence against a tall Sudanese boy,” he said.

“I found out after the grand final.

“I was a bit shocked, I didn’t think I was going to get in because there were really good players there.”

It was this dedication to his sport that saw Michael’s school nominate him for the North Shore Times’ Junior Sports Star Young Achiever award, sponsored by Rebel.

Michael said he is looking forward to the nationals in August.

“In the holidays we’ll be doing three training sessions on the first three days for about seven hours,” he said.

“We’ll be doing some team dinners and playing some rep teams.”

Michael said he hopes to one day be as good as Golden State Warriors’ guard Steph Curry and get drafted to the NBA.

ARE YOU ELIGIBLE?

Junior Sports Star: Athletes aged between 10 and 16

Young Achiever: Athletes aged between 10 and 16

Team Spirit: Athletes aged between 10 and 16

Service to Sport: Volunteers aged 18 and over

 Nominate now at juniorsportsstar.com.au

Leathart, 24, of Pymble, will represent Australia in the 4x100m relay at the ­Commonwealth Games in Glasgow in August.

He said he was confident of his selection after ­winning the national ­championships in April.

“This is the first time I’ve been selected in the Commonwealth Games team,” he said. “I was in the team for the Olympics in London and the world championships last year.”

Leathart, who competes for the Sydney Pacific ­Athletic Club, said the team was selected based on the ­results of the final and what position the athlete would fit in the team.

He said he needed to catch up with his training, after suffering an injury in December.

“I’m doing lots of strength work,” he said.

“When we head overseas there will be plenty of speed and relay work.

“It’s all about minimising the differential. We’ve got good changing abilities with the pass.”
